That&#39;s definitely doable, but it would **not** be as efficient as it could be due to redundant iterations through the `list1`  (just apply `map` and iterate over the `list1` like you&#39;ve done with the `filter`, which is pretty trivial, so I&#39;m leaving it for OP and reader as an exercise, if they are interested in it).

That the example of how it can be done using Java 16 `mapMulty()` in a single stream-statement:
```
List&lt;Student&gt; result = list2.stream()
    .&lt;Student&gt;mapMulti((student, consumer) -&gt; {
        if (student.getId() == null) {
            list1.stream().filter(s -&gt; s.getName().equals(student.getName()))
                .findFirst()
                .ifPresent(consumer);
        }
    }).toList();
```
The **more performant** approach would be to index all the `id` and `name`s of students in the `list1`

To determine which `id` (the first attribute) are present in the `list1` we can generate a `HashSet` it would be way better than iterate through the `list1` over and over.

And to retrieve a student from the `list1` by `name` (in order to replace the student from the `list2` which has an `id` equal to `null`) we can generate a `Map`.

***Sidenote:** don&#39;t use identity comparison `==` to compare the objects if your goal is to compare their properties, and not if the both references point to the same object.*

That&#39;s how it can be implemented:

```
Set&lt;Integer&gt; studentIds = list1.stream()
    .map(Student::getId)
    .collect(Collectors.toSet());
        
Map&lt;String, Student&gt; studentById = list1.stream()
    .collect(Collectors.toMap(
        Student::getName,       // extracting a key
        Function.identity(),    // extracting a value
        (left, right) -&gt; left   // resolving the students mapped to the same key (i.e. having the same name)
    ));
        
List&lt;Student&gt; result = list2.stream()
    .filter(student -&gt; !studentIds.contains(student.getId()))      // ID doesn&#39;t exists in the list1
    .filter(student -&gt; studentById.containsKey(student.getName())) // name is present in the list1
    .map(student -&gt; studentById.get(student.getName()))            // replace student from the list2 with a namesake-student from the list1
    .collect(Collectors.toList());

result.forEach(System.out::println);
```
